T1  - Consumption, government spending, and the real exchange rate
AU  - Ravn, Morten O.
AU  - Schmitt-Grohé, Stephanie
AU  - Uribe, Martín
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 59
IS  - 3
SP  - 215
EP  - 234
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/04/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jmoneco.2012.02.001
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304393212000219
AB  - Using panel structural VAR analysis and quarterly data from four industrialized countries, we document that an increase in government purchases raises output and private consumption, deteriorates the trade balance, and depreciates the real exchange rate. This pattern of comovement poses a puzzle for both neoclassical and Keynesian models. An explanation based on the deep-habit mechanism is proposed. An estimated two-country model with deep-habits is shown to replicate well the observed responses of output, consumption, and the trade balance, and the initial response of the real exchange rate to an estimated government spending shock.
